result.execSummary:
Gypsy Blancharde was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Gypsy Blancharde was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Warrant for Commitment filed by the State and signed and approved by Judge Michael Bohren

Defendant Gypsy Blancharde in court, in custody, with attorney Samuel W. Benedict.   Timothy F. Westphal appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Warrant for commitment and waiver of extradition filed. Defendant waives extradition. Defendant signs extradition papers. Court approves and signs extradition papers and warrant for commitment. Defendant to remain in custody until picked up by the proper authorities from Missouri. Court will give another date in 30 days to see if the defendant has been picked up by authorities from MIssouri. Court will give a review date. If defendant has been transported the hearing will be cancelled.  Hearing scheduled for July 20, 2015 at 08:30 am.
Defendant to have no contact with the co-actor. Not to leave the state of Wisconsin.

Defendant Gypsy Blancharde in court, in custody, with attorney Eryn M Menden.   Attorney appears as friend of the court.  Kevin M. Osborne appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court sets cash bail in the amount of 1 million.  Hearing scheduled for June 29, 2015 at 08:30 am.
